  "response_text": "I can really understand how challenging it must be to feel like an imposter, even when you have all the evidence that you're doing great work. It's so common to doubt yourself, especially when you're achieving things that you once thought were out of reach. Remember, everyone feels this way at times, and it doesn't mean that your accomplishments aren't real or valuable.\n\nIt might help to remind yourself of specific instances where you've excelled or received positive feedback. Writing these down in a journal can be a powerful tool to revisit when you're feeling unsure. Also, try to break down your achievements into smaller, more manageable parts. Celebrate each step along the way, no matter how small it may seem.\n\nAdditionally, talking about your feelings with trusted friends, family members, or colleagues can provide support and validation. Sometimes just sharing what you're going through can lighten the burden. And if you find that imposter syndrome is really impacting your mental health, don't hesitate to seek professional",
